22\n|[[Braun Strowman]] defeated [[Baron Corbin]]\n|{{small|[[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles]] TLC match}}; Since Strowman won, he earned a Universal Championship match at the Royal Rumble and Corbin was stripped of all authoritative power; had Corbin won, he would\u2019ve become the permanent general manager of the Raw brand\n|rowspan=\"2\" |[[TLC: Tables, Ladders & Chairs (2018)|TLC: Tables, Ladders & Chairs]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" |December 16, 2018\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[San Jose, California|San Jose]], [[California]]\n|16:00\n|-\n|align=center|23\n|[[Asuka (wrestler)|Asuka]] defeated [[Becky Lynch]] (c) and [[Charlotte Flair]]\n|{{small|[[Triple threat match|Triple threat]] TLC match for the [[WWE SmackDown Women's Championship]]}}\n|21:45\n|-\n|align=center|24\n|[[King Corbin]] defeated [[Roman Reigns]]\n|{{small|[[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles]] TLC match}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" | [[TLC: Tables, Ladders & Chairs (2019)|TLC: Tables, Ladders & Chairs]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" |December 15, 2019\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Minneapolis, Minnesota]]  \n|22:20\n|-\n|align=center|25\n|The Kabuki Warriors ([[Asuka (wrestler)|Asuka]] and [[Kairi Sane]]) (c) defeated [[Becky Lynch]] and [[Charlotte Flair]]\n|{{small|[[Tag team match|Tag team]] TLC match for the [[WWE Women's Tag Team Championship]]}}\n|26:00\n|}\n\n====Male participants====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Wrestler\n!Victories\n!Appearances\n|- \n|Edge\n|5\n|7\n|-\n|CM Punk \n|3\n|3\n|-\n|Seth Rollins\n|3\n|3\n|-\n|Christian \n|2\n|4\n|-\n|Dean Ambrose\n|2\n|4\n|-\n|Chris Benoit \n|1\n|1\n|-\n|Triple H\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|Shawn Michaels \n|1\n|1\n|-\n|Randy Orton\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|El Torito\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|Bray Wyatt\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|AJ Styles\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|Kurt Angle\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|John Cena\n|1\n|2\n|-\n|Sheamus\n|1\n|2\n|-\n|Braun Strowman\n|1\n|2\n|-\n|Chris Jericho\n|1\n|3\n|-\n|The Miz\n|1\n|3\n|-\n|Roman Reigns\n|1\n|3\n|-\n|Baron Corbin/King Corbin\n|1\n|3\n|-\n|Kane\n|1\n|4\n|-\n|Spike Dudley\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|Rob Van Dam\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|Ric Flair\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|The Undertaker\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|Big Show\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|Jerry Lawler\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|Rey Mysterio\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|Daniel Bryan\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|Hornswoggle\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|Cesaro\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|Alberto Del Rio\n|0\n|2\n|-\n|Ryback\n|0\n|2\n|-\n|Matt Hardy\n|0\n|3\n|-\n|D-Von Dudley\n|0\n|3\n|-\n|Bubba Ray Dudley\n|0\n|4\n|-\n|Jeff Hardy\n|0\n|5\n|}\n\n====Female participants====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Wrestler\n!Victories\n!Appearances\n|-\n|Asuka\n|2\n|2\n|-\n|Kairi Sane\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|Becky Lynch\n|0\n|2\n|-\n|Charlotte Flair\n|0\n|2\n|}\n\n== Usage in other promotions ==\n=== Extreme Championship Wrestling ===\nIn other promotions, the TLC match has quite the following, appealing to a niche market within professional wrestling. Predating the TLC matches, two \"Tables and Ladders matches\" took place. These were traditional matches won by pinfall or submission, not by climbing the ladder for the belts. However, the term \"TLC\" itself was trademarked by WWE, thus other promotions give different names to these types of matches despite having an identical setup. In more hardcore-style promotions, the chairs were often replaced, or were used alongside, chains. One example of a variation of the TLC match is the Tables, Ladders, Chairs, and Canes match. This match is a TLC match with the addition of [[Shinai|Singapore Canes]]. The first and only TLC match was at [[Guilty as Charged (2001)|Guilty as Charged]] on January 7, 2001 at the [[Hammerstein Ballroom]] in [[New York City|New York, New York]], involving [[Steve Corino]], [[Justin Credible]], and [[The Sandman (wrestler)|The Sandman]].\n\n==== Tables and Ladders/Tables, Ladders, Chairs and Canes matches ====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!No.\n!Match\n!Stipulations\n!Event\n!Date\n!Location\n!Length\n|-\n|align=center|1\n|[[The Eliminators]] ([[Perry Saturn]] and [[John Kronus]]) (c) defeated [[Sabu and Rob Van Dam]]\n|{{small|[[Tag team match|Tag team]] Tables & Ladders match for the [[ECW World Tag Team Championship]]}}\n|[[CyberSlam (1997)|CyberSlam]]\n|February 22, 1997\n|[[Philadelphia|Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\n|20:40\n|-\n|align=center|2\n|[[Sabu (wrestler)|Sabu]] defeated [[The Sandman (wrestler)|The Sandman]]\n|{{small|Tables & Ladders match}}\n|[[November to Remember (1997)|November to Remember]]\n|November 30, 1997\n|[[Philadelphia|Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\n|20:55\n|-\n|align=center|3\n|[[The Sandman (wrestler)|The Sandman]] defeated [[Steve Corino]] (c) and [[Justin Credible]]\n|{{small|[[Three-way match|Three-way]] Tables, Ladders, Chairs, & Canes match for the [[ECW World Heavyweight Championship]]}}\n|[[Guilty as Charged (2001)|Guilty as Charged]]\n|January 7, 2001\n|[[New York City|New York, New York]]\n|13:20\n|}\n\n==== Participant list ====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Wrestler\n!Victories\n!Appearances\n|-\n|Perry Saturn\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|John Kronus\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|Sabu\n|1\n|2\n|-\n|The Sandman\n|1\n|2\n|-\n|Rob Van Dam\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|Steve Corino\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|Justin Credible\n|0\n|1\n|}\n\n=== Total Nonstop Action Wrestling/Impact Wrestling ===\nTNA Wrestling used a variation of the TLC match called Full Metal Mayhem as a bout between [[Jeff Hardy]] and [[Abyss (wrestler)|Abyss]] at [[Against All Odds (2005)|Against All Odds 2005]]. The added stipulation to the match was that \"anything metal is legal\", which also included Abyss's trademark chain and bag of tacks.\n\nAbyss defeated [[Jeff Hardy]] by climbing the ladder to retrieve a contract for a shot at the [[NWA World Heavyweight Championship]] on a future episode of ''[[Impact Wrestling (TV series)|TNA Impact!]]''. Abyss was never granted such title shot, and the story was [[retroactive continuity|retconned]] to state he lost his title shot to [[A.J. Styles]] at [[Lockdown (2005)|Lockdown]], even though the shot Styles won was used at [[Hardcore Justice|Hard Justice]] and not on Impact!, though Abyss would later get title shots at [[Slammiversary (2005)|Slammiversary]] and [[No Surrender (2005)|No Surrender]] that year.\n\nTNA used the \"Full Metal Mayhem\" match again at [[Sacrifice (2006)|Sacrifice 2006]] on May 14, 2006 when Abyss went one on one with [[Christian (wrestler)|Christian Cage]] for the [[NWA World Heavyweight Championship]]. Cage defeated Abyss to retain the championship.\n\nIt made its third appearance at [[Victory Road (2008)|Victory Road]] in 2008, in a 6-man tag team match featuring [[Christian (wrestler)|Christian Cage]], [[A.J. Styles]] and [[Rhino (wrestler)|Rhino]] against [[Kurt Angle]] and [[Dudley Boyz|Team 3D]], where Angle pinned Styles to win the match for his team.\n\nTNA held the fourth \"Full Metal Mayhem\" match at [[Bound for Glory (2009)|Bound for Glory 2009]], in which four tag teams ([[The British Invasion (professional wrestling)|The British Invasion]], [[Dudley Boyz|Team 3D]], [[Scott Steiner]] and [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] and [[Beer Money, Inc.]]) competed for both the [[TNA World Tag Team Championship]] and the [[IWGP Tag Team Championship]]. The British Invasion grabbed the TNA World Tag Team Championships whilst Team 3D got the IWGP Tag Team Championships.\n\nOn December 5, 2010, at [[Final Resolution (2010)|Final Resolution]], [[The Motor City Machine Guns]] ([[Alex Shelley]] and [[Chris Sabin]]) defeated [[The Young Bucks|Generation Me]] (Max and Jeremy Buck) to successfully retain the TNA World Tag Team Championship in the fifth \"Full Metal Mayhem\" match.\n\nOn October 16, 2011, at [[Bound for Glory (2011)|Bound for Glory]], [[Rob Van Dam]] defeated [[Jerry Lynn]] in the sixth \"Full Metal Mayhem\" match.\n\nThe seventh edition of the Full Metal Mayhem match occurred on the April 11, 2013 edition of ''[[Impact Wrestling (TV series)|Impact Wrestling]]''. It is the first such match not aired on [[pay-per-view]] and also the first Full Metal Mayhem match to decide the [[TNA World Heavyweight Championship]]. Jeff Hardy was challenging for Bully Ray's championship in a rematch from [[Lockdown (2013)]]. Ray was victorious after sending Hardy through a table from atop the ladder and claiming the belt.\n\nThe November 7, 2013 edition of Full Metal Mayhem match was decided by \"The Wheel of Dixie\", a roulette that determined the match type for all participants in the qualifying tournament for TNA World Heavyweight Title.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=61KVp5jl6RM How Will Dixie Carter Decide the Match Types in The Heavyweight Title Tournament? - Oct. 31, 2013</ref>  On November 7, 2013, Jeff Hardy pinned Chris Sabin to win the first round bout.\n\n==== Full Metal Mayhem matches ====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!No.\n!Match\n!Stipulations\n!Event\n!Date\n!Location\n!Length\n|-\n|align=center| 1\n|[[Abyss (wrestler)|Abyss]] defeated [[Jeff Hardy]]\n|{{small|Full Metal Mayhem match for a shot at the [[NWA World Heavyweight Championship]] on a future episode of ''[[TNA Impact!]]''.}}\n|[[Against All Odds (2005)|Against All Odds]]\n|February 13, 2005\n|[[Orlando, Florida]]\n|15:21\n|-\n|align=center| 2\n|[[Christian Cage]] (c) defeated [[Abyss (wrestler)|Abyss]]\n|{{small|Full Metal Mayhem match for the [[NWA World Heavyweight Championship]].}}\n|[[Sacrifice (2006)|Sacrifice]]\n|May 14, 2006\n|[[Orlando, Florida]]\n|26:01\n|-\n|align=center| 3\n|[[Team 3D]] ([[Bubba Ray Dudley|Brother Ray]] & [[Brother Devon]]) and [[Kurt Angle]] defeated [[Christian Cage]], [[Rhino (wrestler)|Rhino]] and [[A.J. Styles]]\n|{{small|[[Six-man tag team match|Six-man tag team]] Full Metal Mayhem match.}}\n|[[Victory Road (2008)|Victory Road]]\n|July 13, 2008\n|[[Houston|Houston, Texas]]\n|15:55\n|-\n|align=center| 4\n||[[The British Invasion (professional wrestling)|The British Invasion]] ([[Magnus (wrestler)|Brutus Magnus]] & [[Doug Williams (wrestler)|Doug Williams]]; IWGP) and [[Team 3D]] ([[Bubba Ray Dudley|Brother Ray]] & [[Brother Devon]]) defeated [[The Main Event Mafia]] ([[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] & [[Scott Steiner]]; TNA World) and [[Beer Mone