le=Location of Kasarani At Google Maps|last=Google| first=.|publisher=[[Google|Google Maps]]|accessdate=21 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe neighborhood is located along the [[Thika Road]], approximately {{convert|16|km|mi}}, by road, northeast of Nairobi's [[central business district]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=21 March 2015| url=http://distancecalculator.globefeed.com/Kenya_Distance_Result.asp?fromplace=Nairobi%2C%20Kenya&toplace=Kasarani%2C%20Nairobi%2C%20Kenya%2C&dt1=ChIJp0lN2HIRLxgRTJKXslQCz_c&dt2=ChIJuyu6qJsVLxgRje0nA3541PM|\npublisher=Globefeed.com|title=Road Distance Between Downtown Nairobi And Kasarani With Map}}</ref>\n\n==Naming==\nIt is thought that the name \"Kasarani\" originated from a river that flows through the area which has the [[Gikuyu language|Kikuyu]] name \"Gathara-ini\" River. \n\n==Population==\nKasarani's population is estimated to be in excess of 200,000, as at March 2015.{{fact|date=March 2015}}. The neighborhood is subdivided into various [[Ward (country subdivision)|wards]], which include Roysambu, Mwiki, Hunters and Warren. Kasarani lies mostly within the [[Kasarani Constituency|Kasarani parliamentary constituency]] in [[Nairobi County]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=21 March 2015|first= Lucianne| last=Limo|url=http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/thecounties/article/2000106735/voter-wants-kasarani-mp-john-njoroge-chege-removed-from-office|date=12 March 2014|newspaper=[[The Standard (Kenya)]]| title=Voter Wants Kasarani MP John Njoroge Chege Removed From Office}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=21 March 2015| url=http://www.nation.co.ke/counties/nairobi/Thugs-raid-Kasarani-MP-Njoroge-Chege-home-steal-car/-/1954174/2658698/-/ubwimlz/-/index.html|title=Thugs Raid Kasarani MP Njoroge Chege\u2019s Home And Injure Guard|date=19 March 2015 |last=Stella Cherono|first=and Angira Zadock|newspaper=[[Daily Nation]] (Nairobi)}}</ref> It borders [[Juja Constituency]] in Kiambu county.\n\n==Sports==\nKasarani is home to the [[Moi International Sports Centre]], named after former President [[Daniel arap Moi]]. The sports complex has a stadium, gymnasium, swimming pool and hotel. The stadium is used by the [[Kenya national football team|Harambee Stars]] for international matches, and is the home stadium of [[Mathare United]] and [[Tusker F.C.]] of the [[Kenyan Premier League]]. \n\nThe indoor arena is used for volleyball, and is the home venue for the [[Kenya women's national volleyball team]].\n\n==Notable landmarks==\nKasarani is home to the [[USIU Africa]] and [[Pan African Christian University]] campuses. The [[SportView Hotel]] and [[Safari Park Hotel]] are also found here. The area also has the Thika Road Mall (TRM), a shopping complex off the [[Thika Road]] highway.\n\n==Notable Businesses==\n\nKasarani is home to many enterprises. Kasarani is served by several shopping mails such as Mountain Mall, Thika Road Mall (TRM) and Garden City. Super Markets within the area include [[Naivas Limited|Naivas]], Powerstar [[Kassmatt Supermarket]].  [[Www.kasaraniportal.co.ke|Kasarani Portal]], an enterprise listing businesses in Kasarani is located in Seasons Estate.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Githurai]]\n* [[Kahawa]]\n* [[Dandora]]\n* [[Ongata Rongai]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.usiu.ac.ke/ Website of USIU Africa]\n\n{{coord|01|13|44|S|36|54|16|E|display=title}}\n{{nairobi|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Nairobi]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Nairobi]]\n", "name_user": "41.90.46.37", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eNotable Businesses)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kasarani"}
{"title_page": "Industrial Revolution in the United States", "text_new": "The [[Industrial Revolution]] involved a shift in the [[United States]] from manual labor-based industry to technical based industry which greatly increased the overall production and economic growth of the United States, signifying a shift from an [[Agrarian society|agrarian]] to an [[Industrial organization|industrial]] economy widely accepted to have been a result of [[Samuel Slater]]'s introduction of [[Great Britain|British]] Industrial methods in [[textile]] manufacturing to the United States,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/teachers/classroommaterials/primarysourcesets/industrial-revolution/|title=The Industrial Revolution in the United States - Primary Source Set {{!}} Teacher Resources - Library of Congress|website=www.loc.gov|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> and necessitated by the [[War of 1812]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://americanhistory.about.com/od/industrialrev/a/indrevoverview.htm|title=Significant Events of the American Industrial Revolution|website=About.com Education|access-date=2016-05-22|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69N2QhLBq?url=http://americanhistory.about.com/od/industrialrev/a/indrevoverview.htm|archivedate=2012-07-23}}</ref> \n[[File:Samuel Slater industrialist.jpg|thumb|Samuel Slater - \"Father of the American Industrial Revolution\"]]\n\n== Origins == \n{{See also|Economic History of the United States|Samuel Slater}}As Western Europe began industrializing in the late 1700s and early 1800s, the United States remained agrarian in nature with resource processing, such as gristmills and sawmills being its major semi-industrial pursuit,<ref name=\":1\">Taylor, George Rogers (1969). The Transportation Revolution, 1815-1860. {{ISBN|978-0873321013}}.</ref> however, as demand for U.S. resources increased, canals and railroads became extremely important to economic growth due to sparse population<ref>Chandler Jr., Alfred D. (1993). The Visible Hand: The Management Revolution in American Business. Belknap Press of Harvard University Press. {{ISBN|978-0674940529}}</ref> particularly in areas where resources were rich such as in the Western frontier. This made it necessary for the U.S. to expand its technological capabilities, which led to an [[Industrial Revolution]] reaching American shores as entrepreneurs competed and learned from each other to develop better technology, fundamentally and permanently altering the U.S. economy, thrusting it into the new age of industrialization.\n\nThe \"Father of the American Industrial Revolution\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ushistory.org/us/25d.asp|title=The First American Factories [ushistory.org]|website=www.ushistory.org|access-date=2016-05-22}}</ref> Samuel Slater, was born in [[Belper]], [[Derbyshire]], England on June 9, 1768, and began working at a [[cotton mill]] from age 10. He learned that Americans were interested in the Industrial Revolution's new techniques, but since exporting such designs were illegal in England, he memorized as much as he could and departed for New York in 1789 illegally. [[Moses Brown]], a leading [[Rhode Island]] industrialist, attempted to operate a mill with a 32-spindle frame in [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island|Pawtucket]], but he couldn't.  It was at that time that Slater offered his services, promising to replicate British designs for Brown and, after an initial investment by Brown to Slater to fulfill initial requirements, the mill successfully opened in 1793 being the first water-powered roller spinning [[textile mill]] in the Americas. By 1800, Slater's mill had been duplicated by many other entrepreneurs as Slater grew wealthier and his techniques more and more popular, which brought him the name \"Father of the American Industrial Revolution\" by [[Andrew Jackson]] in the U.S., but also the name \"Slater the Traitor\" by many in Great Britain who felt he betrayed them to the Americans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-15002318|title=Samuel Slater: American hero or British traitor?|last=Heath|first=Neil|publisher=BBC News|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n\n== Effects of the First Industrial Revolution ==\n{{See also|Second Industrial Revolution|Technological and industrial history of the United States}}The Industrial Revolution permanently altered the U.S. economy and set the stage for the United States to dominate technological change and growth in the [[Second Industrial Revolution]]<ref>Vatter, Harold G.; Walker, John F.; Alperovitz, Gar (June 1995). \"The onset and persistence of secular stagnation in the U.S. economy: 1910\u20131990, Journal of Economic Issues\".</ref> in its [[Gilded Age]]. The [[American System (economic plan)]] gave way to new economic thought such as the [[Classical economics|classical school of economics]] which assisted in the growth of trade and commerce, but this time with the U.S. as a much larger exporter than importer, which would continue until the late [[Cold War]] era with the drastic increase in imports from [[China]]. The Industrial Revolution also saw a decrease in the rampancy of labor shortages which characterized the U.S. economy in the late 18th and early 19th centuries.<ref>Habakkuk, H. J. (1962). American and British Technology in the Nineteenth Century. London, U.K., New York, USA: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|978-0521094474}}</ref> This was because there was a \"transportation revolution\" that happened in the same period, which was massively important due to the sheer size and low population density of the U.S. at the time, connecting population centers such as through the [[Wilderness Road]] and the [[Erie Canal]], coupled with the development of [[steamboat]]s and [[rail transport]], allowing for the phenomenon of [[urbanization]] to begin which increased the labor force available around larger cities such as [[New York City]] and [[Chicago]], ameliorating the classic American labor shortages of the time. This also allowed for the quicker movement of resources and goods around the country, drastically increasing trade efficiency and output, while allowing for an extensive transport base for the U.S. to grow from in the Second Industrial Revolution.<ref>Eugene S. Ferguson, Oliver Evans, Inventive Genius of the American Industrial Revolution (Hagley Museum & Library, 1980).</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of mill towns in Massachusetts]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Industrial f the United States]]\n{{US-hist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The [[Industrial Revolution]] involved a shift in the [[United States]] from manual labor-based industry to technical based industry which greatly increased the overall production and economic growth of the United States, signifying a shift from an [[Agrarian society|agrarian]] to an [[Industrial organization|industrial]] economy widely accepted to have been a result of [[Samuel Slater]]'s introduction of [[Great Britain|British]] Industrial methods in [[textile]] manufacturing to the United States,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/teachers/classroommaterials/primarysourcesets/industrial-revolution/|title=The Industrial Revolution in the United States - Primary Source Set {{!}} Teacher Resources - Library of Congress|website=www.loc.gov|access-date=2016-05-17}}</ref> and necessitated by the [[War of 1812]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://americanhistory.about.com/od/industrialrev/a/indrevoverview.htm|title=Significant Events of the American Industrial Revolution|website=About.com Education|access-date=2016-05-22|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69N2QhLBq?url=http://americanhistory.about.com/od/industrialrev/a/indrevoverview.htm|archivedate=2012-07-23}}</ref> \n[[File:Samuel Slater industrialist.jpg|thumb|Samuel Slater - \"Father of the American Industrial Revolution\"]]\n\n== Origins == \n{{See also|Economic History of the United States|Samuel Slater}}As Western Europe began industrializing in the late 1700s and early 1800s, the United States remained agrarian in nature with resource processing, such as gristmills and sawmills being its major semi-industrial pursuit,<ref name=\":1\">Taylor, George Rogers (1969). The Transportation Revolution, 1815-1860. {{ISBN|978-0873321013}}.</ref> however, as demand for U.S. resources increased, canals and railroads became extremely important to economic growth due to sparse population<ref>Chandler Jr., Alfred D. (1993). The Visible Hand: The Management Revolution in American Business. Belknap Press of Harvard University Press. {{ISBN|978-0674940529}}</ref> particularly in areas where resources were rich such as in the Western frontier. This made it necessary for the U.S. to expand its technological capabilities, which led to an [[Industrial Revolution]] reaching American shores as entrepreneurs competed and learned from each other to develop better technology, fundamentally and permanently altering the U.S. economy, thrusting it into the new age of industrialization.\n\nThe \"Father of the American Industrial Revolution\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ushistory.org/us/25d.asp|title=The First American Factories [ushistory.org]|website=www.ushistory.org|access-date=2016-05-22}}</ref> Samuel Slater, was born in [[Belper]], [[Derbyshire]], England on June 9, 1768, and began working at a [[cotton mill]] from age 10. He learned that Americans were interested in the Industrial Revolution's new techniques, but since exporting such designs were illegal in England, he memorized as much as he could and departed for New York in 1789 illegally. [[Moses Brown]], a leading [[Rhode Island]] industrialist, attempted to operate a mill with a 32-spindle frame in [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island|Pawtucket]], but he couldn't.  It was at that time that Slater offered his services, promising to replicate British designs for Brown and, after an initial investment by Brown to Slater to fulfill initial requirements, the mill successfully opened in 1793 being the first water-powered roller spinning [[textile mill]] in the Americas. By 1800, Slater's mill had been duplicated by many other entrepreneurs as Slater grew wealthier and his techniques more and more popular, which brought him the name \"Father of the American Industrial Revolution\" by [[Andrew Jackson]] in the U.S., but also the name \"Slater the Traitor\" by many in Great Britain who felt he betrayed them to the Americans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-15002318|title=Samuel Slater: American hero or British traitor?|last=Heath|first=Neil|publisher=BBC News|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n\n== Effects of the First Industrial Revolution ==\n{{See also|Second Industrial Revolution|Technological and industrial history of the United States}}The Industrial Revolution permanently altered the U.S. economy and set the stage for the United States to dominate technological change and growth in the [[Second Industrial Revolution]]<ref>Vatter, Harold G.; Walker, John F.; Alperovitz, Gar (June 1995). \"The onset and persistence of secular stagnation in the U.S. economy: 1910\u20131990, Journal of Economic Issues\".</ref> in its [[Gilded Age]]. The [[American System (economic plan)]] gave way to new economic thought such as the [[Classical economics|classical school of economics]] which assisted in the growth of trade and commerce, but this time with the U.S. as a much larger exporter than importer, which would continue until the late [[Cold War]] era with the drastic increase in imports from [[China]]. The Industrial Revolution also saw a decrease in the rampancy of labor shortages which characterized the U.S. economy in the late 18th and early 19th centuries.<ref>Habakkuk, H. J. (1962). American and British Technology in the Nineteenth Century. London, U.K., New York, USA: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|978-0521094474}}</ref> This was because there was a \"transportation revolution\" that happened in the same period, which was massively important due to the sheer size and low population density of the U.S. at the time, connecting population centers such as through the [[Wilderness Road]] and the [[Erie Canal]], coupled with the development of [[steamboat]]s and [[rail transport]], allowing for the phenomenon of [[urbanization]] to begin which increased the labor force available around larger cities such as [[New York City]] and [[Chicago]], ameliorating the classic American labor shortages of the time. This also allowed for the quicker movement of resources and goods around the country, drastically increasing trade efficiency and output, while allowing for an extensive transport base for the U.S. to grow from in the Second Industrial Revolution.<ref>Eugene S. Ferguson, Oliver Evans, Inventive Genius of the American Industrial Revolution (Hagley Museum & Library, 1980).</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of mill towns in Massachusetts]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Industrial Revolution}}\n{{US history}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Industrial Revolution in the United States}}\n[[Category:Industrial Revolution|United States]]\n[[Category: Industry in the United States]]\n[[Category: Industrial history of the United States]]\n{{US-hist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "106.208.74.130", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Industrial_Revolution_in_the_United_States"}
